Thank you for sending the questions! I enjoyed the #AskUdacityAnything session. It's me @EmilyLindemer signing off!
Learn how to develop those skills and so many doors will open for you.

For example, you'll encounter issues of missing data over and over again in your career. A good AI scientist cleans the data, finds what's complete, and builds a model on it. A great AI scientist thinks creatively and finds proxies for data that are missing.
The technical skills are probably the most obvious. Python, R, SQL, etc. The skills that I think are more important are cognitive problem-solving skills and creativity.

Do projects that you find interesting in fields that you care about. Think of how you can translate your questions about the world into data problems. Then, use the tools and skills you have to go and answer them. Don't wait for someone to come to you with the questions.
Learn the tools, and learn how to work with data. Data is messy!! I can't emphasize enough how important it is to learn how to approach complex and messy data problems. It comes through practice.
#AskUdacityAnything What skills are necessary for an #AI professional to make a successful career in this field?

We are taking last few questions! #AskUdacityAnything
#ArtificialIntelligence #AI #Data https://t.co/cEkfg6iPRT
I would of course also recommend all of the wonderful free @udacity courses!

Then, maybe we could develop drugs that actually *prevent* Alzheimer's rather than just treating its symptoms. Did you know that if we could delay the onset of the disease by just 5 years, 40% of nursing home beds in the US would be empty? Think about that!

Here's an example. I did my PhD research in #AlzheimersDisease. Right now, we don't know if you're going to get it until you get it, and at that point, it's too late. What if we could predict who would get it 10 years earlier? 20 years?

There are an infinite number of cool things you can do with #AI, some might make you rich, some might be for pure entertainment, but I think that the most exciting opportunities are the ones that will change humanity in a positive way.
Well, I'm biased of course, but I would say that the most exciting thing you can do is use your technology to help humans and help the planet.
#AskUdacityAnything @EmilyLindemer What can aspirants do now to prepare for a #FutureInAI?
Hi @EmilyLindemer  What is the most exciting thing you can do with #AI and #DataScience? #AskUdacityAnything

Years ago, when I was trying to make the switch from #machinelearning to #deeplearning in my career, I learned a tremendous amount from https://t.co/YUeZb4DJlK and would highly recommend as a free resource!
Students can help by anticipating these challenges in the early days of AI development, and learning the cutting-edge tools in the industry for scaling.

I'd say that scaling is one of the biggest challenges. It's one thing to build a model that works on a static set of data, and it's an entirely different animal to build and productionalize a model that scales and is robust to new data.

There was such an abundance of information during #covid that my strategy was to read as much as possible and look for both strong signals that kept surfacing, as well as little blips of interesting information that didn't feel connected yet.

Great question! I started my career studying #neuroscience which has a lot of overlap with #computerscience. Studying both led me to a career in research during a very exciting time for #AI, particularly in #healthcare, and I got hooked!
#AskUdacityAnything - @EmilyLindemer, what are the biggest challenges organizations face while implementing #ArtificialIntelligence? And, how can students help?
Hi @EmilyLindemer, How did you get into this field? How do you keep yourself updated, especially during emergencies like #epidemics or #pandemics? #AskUdacityAnything
Understanding the nuances of data in a particular field (where the gaps usually are, how reliable the data are, proxies that you can develop for missing data, etc) is invaluable!

A softer skill that I don't see people talk about as much but is incredibly important is in gaining subject matter expertise. In #healthcare, I'd much prefer to work with a data scientist who has used ICD and NDC codes before than one who has not.

I cannot emphasize enough how much better of a data scientist you will be if you understand what's going on under the hood of sklearn.ensemble.RandomForestClassifier rather than just filling in parameters that you copied from an example.
A fundamental understanding of #statistics also goes a *long way*

I've never been in a data science setting where #python or #R wasn't used, so definitely make sure you know those! Learn how to connect these tools to cloud databases like #bigquery or #AWS so that you can work with #bigdata at scale.
Last 30min! #AskUdacityAnything https://t.co/TsfaYAifwN
#AskUdacityAnything Are there any free online resources that you recommend for people interested in learning more about #AI and #Data?
Check out what some of these awesome companies are doing: https://t.co/fGvvCFa2xm

I would say that ventures in #mHealth that improve access to #healthcare in Latin American will also have the added benefit of extending our ability to collect data more broadly, which in turn will enable better #AI opportunities.

When it comes to #AI, this poses a huge problem for collecting data. You can't do *anything* with AI unless you have data. So, if you have a significant portion of the population who doesn't have access, you probably don't have much data on them to learn from.

One thing that's significant about Latin America's healthcare is that *so* many patients lack access due to living in rural areas. While this is also true in the US, it's a bigger issue in Latin America.
Hi Emily! being in the field for long, what must-have tools or technologies do you suggest for #data professionals in 2021 and beyond? post-#COVID19 #AskUdacityAnything

@MukeshTekwani4 @EmilyLindemer That would be really interesting! I think with this new explosion of remote and online learning, there's a real opportunity to deliver tailored content to students based on areas of strengths and weaknesses, which I can imagine AI/ML playing a role in.

Jordan Huayhua asks - What is the main problem that Latin America struggle when they try to start an #AI or #DataScience healthcare project? What do you recommend for people who wants to start in these field? #AskUdacityAnything
I also loved building the final project, because it was a real-world problem that I think captures what you might encounter in an actual career in #AI for #medicalimaging

I loved so much about this nanodegree! Building it allowed me to use a different part of my brain that I haven't been able to in a while -- the part that is used for breaking down complex concepts and communicating them to a beginner. It was so rewarding.
#AIscientists need to help solve the #blackbox problem for healthcare.

#radiologists are experts who can recognize tens of thousands of findings across images of the entire human body. We're nowhere near those type of algorithms and even if we were, a lot of trust still needs to be gained (and rightfully so) of AI by healthcare professionals.
That's a tough question! In many industries, it already has. Coming back to #healthcareAI, however, in my experience we're still really far away from that. Let's take #medicalimaging for example.
What is your favorite part about working on #AI  for #Healthcare nanodegree? @EmilyLindemer #AskUdacityAnything

Going back to #expertsystems, this is basically equivalent to what we call "clinical decision-making" in healthcare, and I do believe that there will be lots of growth there in the next couple of years as well.
When we talk about @healthcareAI, however, I really think that #NLP is going to be one of the most important branches due to the tremendous amount of unstructured data that we have on patients.

Another great question. This definitely depends on the industry that you're talking about. For example, lots of industries (like finance and manufacturing) have been benefitting from #expertsystems for quite some time, and can advance themselves along that branch even further.
Hi Emily! Will #AI actually take away our jobs? Should I be worried as an AI enthusiast? #AskUdacityAnything

Finally, #diseaseprediction has been around for quite some time, but as we are now in this world of learning new things about #covid (like long-haulers and delayed symptoms) disease prediction is taking on an entirely new meaning.

In terms of #dataharmonization, healthcare is so challenging because patient data comes in so many forms (notes, lab tests, images, etc) and while it may be straightforward to create an #AI model on a small set of this disparate data, it's a different animal to do it at scale

In terms of #NLP, one of our biggest sources of data in healthcare are patient notes, which are #unstructureddata. We need to develop sophisticated #NLP to extract meaning from this type of data, which is becoming even more important post-COVID.

Great question! I see a few major trends in #healthcareAI that are dominating post-#COVID:
1. Natural language processing
2. Data harmonization
3. Prediction 

I'll elaborate more...
